solutions.content:
Funny one and today I decided to give myself an extra challenge using as little memory as possible, so, first of all I declared the following variables:
* 2 pointers, `i` and `j`, both set to `0`, to keep track of how we go through each string;
* 2 variables to store the length of each string, `v1Len` and `v2Len` (slightly better than calling `.size()` all the time or so they say;
* 2 containers of the current sub-values being parsed, `n1` and `n2`.

I then proceed to loop until `i < v1Len || j < v2Len`, meaning the loop will stop on its own only when I finish parsing both strings; that is an important distinctions, since if we are done with one and still in the loop, we want to parse the other and then still compare the values (the one we finished parsing will be at `0`).

Inside the loop, we set both `n1` and `n2` to `0` and then we advanced our pointers and at the same time we increase their respective values (10 times the previous value, plus the value of the current digit, computed converting from char to a value in the `0 - 9` range substracting the value of the char `'0'`). Also notice that this way we can easily get rid of leading `0`s without the need of any further logic.

We then compare the subvalues `n1` and `n2` and leave the loop if they differ; we proceed with the next sub-values otherwise.

If we terminate parsing both strings and exit the loop, then it means all the values so far were equals, thus we return `0` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int compareVersion(string v1, string v2) {
        // support variables
        int i = 0, j = 0, v1Len = v1.size(), v2Len = v2.size(), n1, n2;
        while (i < v1Len || j < v2Len) {
            // computing the next set of version sub-values
            n1 = 0;
            n2 = 0;
            while (i < v1Len && v1[i] != '.') n1 = n1 * 10 + (v1[i++] - '0');
            while (j < v2Len && v2[j] != '.') n2 = n2 * 10 + (v2[j++] - '0');
            // handling possible results
            if (n1 < n2) return -1;
            else if (n1 > n2) return 1;
            i++;
            j++;
        }
        return 0;
    }
};
```

