String split in java takes regex as a parameter and not any character which you want to split a string by. So `version1.split(".")` is wrong, **it should be** `version1.split("\\.")`. `'.'` in a regular expression means any character, use `'\\'` to escape it.

Doc: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#split-java.lang.String-

```
class Solution {

    private int compareVersion(String version1, String version2, int flip) {
        String[] v1 = version1.split("\\.");
        String[] v2 = version2.split("\\.");
        int i, x, y;
        for(i=0; i<v1.length; i++){
            x = Integer.parseInt(v1[i]);
            y = Integer.parseInt(v2[i]);
            if(x>y) return 1*flip;
            else if(x<y) return -1*flip;
        }
        for(; i<v2.length; i++){
            if(Integer.parseInt(v2[i])!=0) return -1*flip;
        }
        return 0;
    }

    public int compareVersion(String version1, String version2) {
        if(version1.length() > version2.length()) return compareVersion(version2, version1, -1);
        else return compareVersion(version1, version2, 1);
    }
}
```
P.S: the flippity dippity I did is just to make it more consise :p

